{
  "texts": [
    "A poset is atomic iff for every non-minimum element x ∈ S, there is an atom a such that a ⊑ x.",
    "◁ This is not quite the notion we want for possibility frames (though it would be fine for the extended frames of § 4.3), so we define atomic possibility frames a bit differently.Definition 4.14 (Minimal Points and Atomic Frames).",
    "A minimal point in a poset ⟨S, ⊑⟩ is an a ∈ S such that for all x ∈ S, if x ⊑ a, then x = a.Let min⟨S, ⊑⟩ be the set of minimal points in ⟨S, ⊑⟩.",
    "A partial-state frameF = ⟨S, ⊑, {R i } i∈I, P ⟩ is atomic iff for every x ∈ S, there is an a ∈ min⟨S, ⊑⟩ such that a ⊑ x.",
    "◁This notion of atomic is the flipped version of what is called the McKinsey condition [Chagrov and Zakharyaschev, 1997, p. 82], the condition that for all x ∈ S, there is a y ∈ max⟨S, ⊑⟩ such that x ⊑ y.Note that the condition of atomicity concerns only the poset ⟨S, ⊑⟩, not the set P of admissible propositions."
  ]
}